    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>The Muhammad Cartoon Furor</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Hala Innab letter criticizes European newspapers that published offensive cartoons of Prophet Muhammad</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>The issue is not whether European papers have the right to publish offensive cartoons of the Prophet Muhammad. The issue is abuse of freedom and the lack of responsibility.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>The issue is not whether European papers have the right to publish offensive cartoons of the Prophet Muhammad. The issue is abuse of freedom and the lack of responsibility.</p>
        <p>The function of newspapers is to inform, not inflame. At a time when the relationship between Islamic and Western countries is strained, one would expect more from reputable newspapers.</p>
        <p>How would Americans feel if The New York Times decided to print jokes about the Jewish Holocaust or African slavery, just to test our reaction?</p>
        <p>Hala Innab  Amman, Jordan, Feb. 3, 2006</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
